Q1: Collect and Analyze Security Logs [10 Marks]
Linux System Logs
Log File	Location	What It Records
Auth Log	/var/log/auth.log	Login attempts, sudo usage
System Log	/var/log/syslog	System events, errors
Kernel Log	/var/log/kern.log	Kernel messages
Failed Logins	/var/log/btmp	Failed login attempts
Current Logins	/var/log/wtmp	Login history
Windows System Logs
Log Type	Location	What It Records
Security	Event Viewer → Windows Logs	Logins, privilege changes
Application	Event Viewer → Windows Logs	App errors, crashes
System	Event Viewer → Windows Logs	System events, drivers
Setup	Event Viewer → Windows Logs	Software installation
Key Event IDs to Monitor (Windows)
Event ID	Meaning
4624	Successful login
4625	Failed login
4648	Logon with explicit credentials
4672	Admin login
4688	Process created
4720	User account created
4728	User added to admin group
Commands to Collect Logs (Linux)
bash
# View auth logs
sudo cat /var/log/auth.log

# View last 10 failed logins
sudo lastb | head -10

# View login history
last

# View real-time logs
sudo tail -f /var/log/auth.log

# Search for suspicious patterns
grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log
grep "sudo" /var/log/auth.log
Commands to Collect Logs (Windows PowerShell)
powershell
# Get security events
Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{LogName='Security'; ID=4625} -MaxEvents 50

# Get failed logins
Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{LogName='Security'; ID=4625}

# Get admin logins
Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{LogName='Security'; ID=4672}

# Export logs to file
wevtutil epl Security C:\logs\security.evtx



